  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Postscript to the Poetry Scroll of Boksan
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Sikmuoae is one who cherishes poetry above all else. Once he journeyed to the capital, seeking verses from princes and ministers. The esteemed Heo of the Department of State Affairs and the learned Sae of the Hanlin Academy—men of renown in the court—all bestowed their poems upon him. From that time forward, wherever a voice of poetic talent was heard, whether near or far, he would hasten to seek it out. Thus have the scholars and gentlemen of our Eastern Kingdom come to hold him dear.

    Late yesterday, Boksan came bearing his poetry scroll, asking me to inscribe this postscript. Though I have never met Boksan, I know him thus: in the deep mountains and remote valleys, his form becomes like withered wood, his heart like cold ash. Yet he who seeks what others call emptiness and extinction—he turns his mind to the healing arts, wandering restlessly across ten thousand li, hastening to give life to others while giving little thought to his own gain. Such a man reveals his true nature.

    Compared to those who shirk their duties, disorder the bonds of kinship, and burden the world with nothing but harm, he stands apart entirely. Now, as he returns to the south, a poet has recorded his deeds. Having already grown fond of Sikmuoae and finding his request difficult to refuse, I inscribe these words upon his scroll.
  footnotes:
    - Sikmuoae (式無外) is likely a courtesy name or title meaning 'without external distinctions,' suggesting a person of refined character.
    - The imagery of 'withered wood' and 'cold ash' references Buddhist and Daoist spiritual practices, suggesting Boksan's ascetic spiritual orientation.
    - The 'Eastern Kingdom' (東國) refers to Korea.
    - The scroll is being inscribed as a testimonial to Boksan's virtue, particularly his dedication to healing and service rather than personal advancement.
